AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation Project¶

Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?`
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description: Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Executing K-means Clustering¶

In [220]:
##Scale the data
from scipy.stats import zscore

df_zscore = df.apply(zscore)

Using all data including Customer_key columns for elbow analysis¶

In [221]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters_1=range(1,20)
Avg_Distortions=[]

for k in clusters_1:
    model_1= KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model_1.fit(df_zscore)
    prediction=model_1.predict(df_zscore)
    
    # average of the minimum distance between data points and centroid
    Avg_Distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_zscore, model_1.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df.shape[0])                 
    
    
plt.plot(clusters_1, Avg_Distortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[221]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

No distinct elbow seen, K = 7 could be selected if customer_key data is included

Running analysis with different linkages and comparing the resultant cophenet index to get the best linkage method and dendogram¶
In [234]:
# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
# closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
c = []
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete','average','weighted','centroid','ward']
for i in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(df_H_z, metric='euclidean', method= i)
    c.append(cophenet(Z, pdist(df_H_z)))
pd.DataFrame(c, columns =['cophenetic coef', 'array'], index = linkage_methods).drop('array', axis = 1)

Observations¶

  1. In terms of the appropraite dendogram and linkage method, height of each link in a cluster tree with the heights of neighboring links below it in the tree would be used for selecting the best splits. This would be combined with the cophenet coeff to strike a balance.

  2. A link that is approximately the same or less height as the links below it indicates that there are no distinct divisions between the objects joined at this level of the hierarchy.

  3. based on this facts, the Ward Linkage Method shows a distinct clusters and great height difference between links above and bwlow. It also have a cophenet coeff. of 0.74 which is good enough.

  4. Although the average, weighted & centroid linkage method yielded the highest cophenet coeff of 0.9169, 0.9133 and 0.9134 respectively, they are no near Ward method when the distance of seperation of clusters is considered.

Below is the Ward -Linkage -method dendrogram with the optimal distance between clusters which would be used as input for clustering data¶

  1. They both performed very well in creating distinct clusters of the data
  2. Based on Silhouette score, both performed above average with K-means slightly higher in performance.
  3. Based on the number of data points in each group for both K-Means and Hierarchical, their is a degree of consistency as the data points are almost equal.
  4. Due to the similarity observed in both methods, it could be deduced that the chosen number of clusters K= 3 is optimum.
  5. K-Means clustering runs was less computationally demanding compare to Hierarchical clusters
  6. K-Means assignes zero(0) to the first cluster while Hierarchical assignes 1 to the first cluster

  2. Group 1 in hierachical cluster which is also group 1 in K-means clusters have customers with the lowest category of credit limit and largest number of customers that reached the bank through call centers. The also posses lowest number of total credit cards.

  3. Group 3 in hierachical cluster which is also group 0 in K-means have the largest number of customers that phyisically visited the bank, and second largest customers with credit limit and total number of credit card. This group is the least in online visit.
